The code passes lint and type checks. Let me provide a summary of the fix.

## Bug Summary
The 3D head model was not properly centered because the bounding box was calculated BEFORE scaling, causing the centering offset to be applied in unscaled coordinates which then got scaled along with the model.

## Root Cause
- File: `/Users/imorgado/LOOKSMAXX/looksmaxx-app/src/components/HeadScene.tsx` (lines 339-365)
- The bug occurs because the original code calculated the bounding box center on the unscaled model, then applied that offset as `model.position.set(-center.x, -center.y, -center.z)`, and THEN scaled the model. When the model is scaled, the position offset also gets scaled by the same factor, resulting in incorrect centering.

## Trace Path
1. Error manifests as model appearing off-center in the scene
2. <- `model.position.set(-initialCenter.x, -initialCenter.y, -initialCenter.z)` uses unscaled center values
3. <- `model.scale.set(scaleFactor, scaleFactor, scaleFactor)` then scales BOTH geometry AND position offset
4. <- `initialBox.getCenter()` calculated on unscaled model <- ROOT CAUSE

## Fix Applied
Changed the order of operations to match the original `model.js`:

**Before (incorrect):**
```typescript
// 1. Calculate bounding box (unscaled)
const initialBox = new THREE.Box3().setFromObject(model);
const initialCenter = initialBox.getCenter(new THREE.Vector3());

// 2. Set position offset (unscaled values)
model.position.set(-initialCenter.x, -initialCenter.y, -initialCenter.z);

// 3. Scale model (this also scales the position offset!)
model.scale.set(scaleFactor, scaleFactor, scaleFactor);
```

**After (correct, matching original):**
```typescript
// 1. Scale FIRST
model.scale.set(scaleFactor, scaleFactor, scaleFactor);
model.updateMatrixWorld(true);

// 2. THEN calculate bounding box (on scaled model)
const box = new THREE.Box3().setFromObject(model);
const center = box.getCenter(new THREE.Vector3());

// 3. Create headGroup at origin
const headGroup = new THREE.Group();
headGroup.position.set(0, 0, 0);

// 4. Offset model position (using scaled center values)
model.position.x = -center.x;
model.position.y = -center.y;
model.position.z = -center.z;
model.rotation.x = 0;
model.updateMatrixWorld(true);
```

## Prevention
When centering a 3D model that will be scaled:
1. Always scale first, then calculate bounding box
2. Alternatively, if you must calculate on unscaled model, multiply the offset by the scale factor
3. Add a test that verifies the final bounding box center is at (0, 0, 0) after centering

